A change is on the way!
Prism Ray Online Services (PROS) was originally created through a collaboration between Saber Interactive and PLAION / Deep Silver. To bring more clarity to our game catalog, we're introducing a split in the platform.
Going forward
PLAION / Deep Silver games will move to a new platform called Deep Silver Account, accessible at account.deepsilver.com.
Saber Interactive games will remain on Prism Ray Online Services (PROS) at prismray.io.
What does this mean for you? Until now, you’ve been using prismray.io to access your rewards, statistics, and game-related features.
Now, you’ll be able to log in to both the PROS and Deep Silver platforms using the same account credentials.

{extras={}, sender_person=android.app.Person@ddbdbf63, sender=Tadi Channel, text=I came across a video of cool looking phenomenon from a boomer channel on tg (flat earthers this time). It was atmospheric turbulence which they obviously interpreted as stars being fake. The worst thing is that no video I found elsewhere looks as good as theirs. Guess they were the only ones to care to magnify it or the only ones to think of Nikon P1000 as a good telescope (otherwise it's a great camera for its original purpose).

After ~10 minutes of searching for a comparable video I found just one:
https://youtube.com/watch?v=ooeRUOZ0Gi4

Imagine it at a much higher res, slowed down and used as an animated wallpaper. That would be something. Subpar optics can often be unexpectedly fascinating, and same goes also for sensors. Every artifact can be recreated in post, but for artistic purposes it's always best to pick the real thing., time=1754826052000}

get_state_attribute.name: Advanced example: Get state/attribute from other entities
get_state_attribute.creator: Clooos
get_state_attribute.description:
Get state/attribute from other entities and replace the default state/attribute field. Configure this module via the editor or in YAML, for example: 

get_state_attribute:
    - entity: weather.home
    - entity: sensor.weather_station
      attribute: humidity
    - entity: sensor.weather_station
      attribute: temperature

If it doesn't work, make sure at least one of "Show state" or "Show attribute" is turned on in your card configuration.

badgy-condition-helper.name: Badgy Condition Helper
badgy-condition-helper.creator: HyperCriSiS
badgy-condition-helper.description:
Advanced badge and effect helper module with conditional logic.

Features:
- Entity badges: Display entity states or attributes on sub-buttons
- Icon badges: Show icon indicators on sub-buttons
- Sub-button backgrounds: Change background colors based on conditions
- Icon effects: Apply animations to main and sub-button icons
- Badge effects: Apply animations to badges
- Main icon background: Change the main icon background conditionally
- Sub-button effects: Apply animations (including color for glow) to the entire sub-button container

All features support Home Assistant-style conditions for state-based logic.

dynamic_lighting.name: Dynamic lighting styling
dynamic_lighting.creator: Timmy
dynamic_lighting.description:
This module provides dynamic styling based on light states and ambient illuminance levels.
The background, border, and text colors adapt based on whether lights are on (using their RGB color)
or off (using illuminance sensor values for natural lighting effects).

Required entities:
- A light entity (for RGB state and on/off status)
- An illuminance sensor (for ambient light levels)
Optional:
- A switch entity (as additional power state input)

temperature_colouring.name: Temperature colouring
temperature_colouring.creator: Timmy
temperature_colouring.description:
This module provides dynamic colouring based on temperature sensor values.
Colour adjustments are applied to selected sub-buttons and/or state display elements.

Required entities:
- A temperature sensor

You can configure which elements should receive dynamic colouring:
- Sub-buttons (1-6)
- State display

Example YAML configuration:

temperature_colouring:
  temperature_sensor: sensor.kitchen_temperature
  elements:
    sub_buttons: [1, 3, 5]  # Apply to sub-buttons 1, 3, and 5
    state_display: true     # Apply to state display element

rmn_conditional_background_color.name: Conditional Background Color
rmn_conditional_background_color.creator: andarotajo
rmn_conditional_background_color.description:
This module allows you to change the background color of a card based on one or more conditions and optionally the opacity.
For the conditions, the default selector of Home Assistant is used, allowing for a wide range of conditions. The background color can be changed based on three different modes: - Preset Color: Uses a predefined color from the Home Assistant theme. - Color Wheel: Allows you to select a color using a color wheel. - CSS Variable: Uses a custom CSS variable to set the background color.
It's possible to set up multiple color/condition pairs by copying the "background_1" block and incrementing the number. While the name doesn't have to end with a number since the code looks for "background_", it is recommended to do so for clarity.

progress_bar.description: Show a progress bar on "State" buttons, much like how sliders appear. Also supports different colors for custom conditions.

humidity_colouring.name: Humidity Colouring
humidity_colouring.creator: Timmy
humidity_colouring.description:
This module provides dynamic colour styling based on humidity levels.
It allows selecting sub-buttons (1-6) and the state display to reflect humidity values.

Required entity:
- A humidity sensor (mandatory)

Configure this module via the editor or in YAML, for example:

humidity_colouring:
  humidity_sensor: sensor.kitchen_humidity
  elements:
    sub_buttons: [1, 3, 5]  # Apply to sub-buttons 1, 3, and 5
    state_display: true      # Apply to state display element
